{"term":"2012","caseName":"Salinas v. Texas","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/12-246","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 17, 2013","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/21648","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument next in Case 12-246, Salinas v. Texas.","start":0,"stop":5.718,"duration":5.72},{"text":"Mr. Fisher.","start":5.718,"stop":6.737,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":6.737,"stop":9.456,"duration":2.72},{"text":"The Fifth Amendment prohibits using a person's silence during a noncustodial police interview against him at trial, and nothing about the specific facts of this case give this Court cause to refrain from applying that rule here.","start":9.456,"stop":22.846,"duration":13.39},{"text":"To the contrary, the State's closing argument in this case urging the jury to find Mr. Salinas guilty because, quote,","start":22.846,"stop":29.769,"duration":6.92},{"text":"\"an innocent person would have denied law enforcement's accusations. \"","start":29.769,"stop":33.387,"duration":3.62},{"text":"strikes at the core of everything the Griffin rule, and indeed the Fifth Amendment, is designed to prohibit.","start":33.387,"stop":38.106,"duration":4.72},{"text":"It evokes an inquisitorial system of justice.","start":38.106,"stop":41.208,"duration":3.1},{"text":"It effectively shifts the burden of proof onto the defendant, and it demeans individual dignity by conscripting the defendant as a product of his own demise.","start":41.208,"stop":51.033,"duration":9.83},{"text":"Now, the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals resisted this logic and held the Fifth Amendment didn't apply, because there was supposedly no compulsion in this case in the sense that there was no physical or psychological coercion of the kind that's inherent in custody.","start":51.033,"stop":64.406,"duration":13.37},{"text":"But the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals simply misunderstood the nature of a Griffin claim and the nature of the compulsion.","start":64.406,"stop":71.679,"duration":7.27},{"text":"The compulsion that Mr. Salinas faced was when the police asked him the question about ballistics evidence, there was nothing he could do to avoid supplying the State with incriminating evidence that it could use against him.","start":71.679,"stop":84.154,"duration":12.47},{"text":"If he answered the question--","start":84.154,"stop":85.387,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Why isn't it -- why isn't it like the Berg -- is it Berghuis case?","start":85.387,"stop":88.974,"duration":3.59},{"text":"There was a case of someone who was given Miranda warnings and even so, the Court said he was silent.","start":88.974,"stop":97.414,"duration":8.44},{"text":"He didn't invoke the Fifth Amendment, therefore, his silence can be commented on.","start":97.414,"stop":105.567,"duration":8.15}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, that's not the holding of the Berghuis case, with all due respect.","start":105.567,"stop":108.935,"duration":3.37},{"text":"The Berghuis case was about whether his subsequent statements could be used against him.","start":108.935,"stop":112.773,"duration":3.84},{"text":"This Court didn't hold that his silence that preceded those statements could be used against him, and indeed, that would be contrary to Miranda itself in footnote 37 where the Court said, if somebody stands mute in a custodial setting in the face of law enforcement accusations, they may not be--","start":112.773,"stop":127.849,"duration":15.08}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Then what's the law?","start":127.849,"stop":129.033,"duration":1.18},{"text":"What is.","start":129.033,"stop":129.566,"duration":0.53},{"text":"I mean, Joe Smith leaves a -- a blank in part of his tax return.","start":129.566,"stop":133.92,"duration":4.35},{"text":"The IRS gets it, later it turns out to be relevant, and the prosecutor wants to say, hey, he left this blank.","start":133.92,"stop":141.007,"duration":7.09},{"text":"Okay?","start":141.007,"stop":141.859,"duration":0.85},{"text":"Now, Griffin doesn't apply, right?","start":141.859,"stop":143.625,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--If the--","start":143.625,"stop":145.31,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, isn't it -- you're not going to say that any -- any time you refuse to tell the government anything, and later on it turns out to be relevant to a criminal prosecution, that that's taken as an invocation of the Fifth Amendment.","start":145.31,"stop":156.333,"duration":11.02},{"text":"I mean, do you want to go that far?","start":156.333,"stop":157.485,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, I don't need to.","start":157.485,"stop":158.385,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":158.385,"stop":159.102,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Then you need a line.","start":159.102,"stop":159.904,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"This case is--","start":159.904,"stop":160.42,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Then what is -- then you need a line.","start":160.42,"stop":161.554,"duration":1.13},{"text":"So where is -- there's the tax case; then we have a case they're selling tickets to the policeman's ball and somebody comes to the door and the policeman says, hey, I haven't seen you around before, and he doesn't answer.","start":161.554,"stop":172.795,"duration":11.24},{"text":"Okay?","start":172.795,"stop":174.028,"duration":1.23},{"text":"Now, that's probably not an invocation.","start":174.028,"stop":177.047,"duration":3.02},{"text":"And then we have the clear line, which in custody, and now you want to extend that line.","start":177.047,"stop":182.818,"duration":5.77},{"text":"And so what I want to know if I follow you and extend it, what line do I draw?","start":182.818,"stop":187.887,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, it's sufficient to decide this case to say that a noncustodial police interview during the investigation of a crime where they're interviewing somebody about -- who is -- who is, as the State concedes, a suspect in a crime.","start":187.887,"stop":202.831,"duration":14.94},{"text":"Now, it may well be that Griffin extends a little bit further, and remember, the Solicitor General at least agrees that Griffin applies in a noncustodial setting.","start":202.831,"stop":209.151,"duration":6.32}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but it's -- it's well settled that when you're -- wherein you're examining the witness and he takes -- and he suddenly says I don't want any more questions, that that's -- he's waived if you're in court, if you're examining a witness on the stand.","start":209.151,"stop":223.811,"duration":14.66},{"text":"So against that background, suppose in this case the facts were just about the same, and he said what -- the police said, what would you do if we matched the shotgun shells, and he said -- he said “ Well ” -- and then he starts to cry.","start":223.811,"stop":235.968,"duration":12.16},{"text":"He said one word, “ Well ”, and he started to cry.","start":235.968,"stop":239.189,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Admissible?","start":239.189,"stop":239.989,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that would be admissible, but it would be forbidden for the--","start":239.989,"stop":243.224,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Because he said, “ Well ”?","start":243.224,"stop":244.258,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":244.258,"stop":244.924,"duration":0.67},{"text":"That word would be admissible if the State had--","start":244.924,"stop":246.543,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but could the police officer also testify that and then he started to cry?","start":246.543,"stop":250.728,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Perhaps.","start":250.728,"stop":252.264,"duration":1.54},{"text":"But the State -- what the State would not be able to do would be to argue that his silence and refusal to answer the question demonstrated his guilt.","start":252.264,"stop":259.418,"duration":7.15}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Or the prosecution could say, Well, he said, well, and started to cry, and he never told us anything else.","start":259.418,"stop":262.603,"duration":3.19},{"text":"That -- that final sentence that I used is impermissible?","start":262.603,"stop":266.673,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that may well cross the line.","start":266.673,"stop":268.289,"duration":1.62},{"text":"You have the exact issue that arises already in custodial settings, where under Doyle and footnote 37 of Miranda you've held that silence can't be used against a criminal defendant.","start":268.289,"stop":278.231,"duration":9.94},{"text":"So, Justice Kennedy, you're right that questions will arise in two ways.","start":278.231,"stop":281.849,"duration":3.62},{"text":"One is whether words that the defendant uses are tantamount to refusing to answer the question, and then there is a second question about physical demeanor evidence.","start":281.849,"stop":290.622,"duration":8.77},{"text":"The law is already sorted out on this in the lower courts, and I think it's a very workable test.","start":290.622,"stop":296.026,"duration":5.4},{"text":"The Solicitor General agrees with what it is, and the reason why this Court hasn't seen a case, itself seen a case like that, is because once the rule is established that the prosecution can't use silence against the defendant, the temptation drops away to try to introduce that evidence for some supposedly different purpose.","start":296.026,"stop":312.904,"duration":16.88}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Fisher, but then -- do -- do I understand correctly that you're saying demeanor is different, so, although it was impermissible to comment on silence, it was okay to say he looked down, he seemed to be sweating, he was very nervous, he was shuffling his feet.","start":312.904,"stop":333.032,"duration":20.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Insofar as demeanor evidence that the State offers has communicative values and the State argues that it has communicative value, independent of simply what the defendant looked like when he remains silent, then it -- then it may well be able to introduce that evidence.","start":333.032,"stop":347.641,"duration":14.61},{"text":"Now, as I said, as I was just finishing up telling Justice Kennedy, you're not going to have hard cases in this respect because once the temptation -- once it's clear that silence can't be used, then the prosecution I think has little motivation to try to walk that line.","start":347.641,"stop":361.718,"duration":14.08},{"text":"And indeed, I think it would be appropriate in a case if the prosecution said, look, the fact that the defendant started we think is relevant for some reason independent of what he -- of failing to answer the question.","start":361.718,"stop":372.026,"duration":10.31},{"text":"The jury could be instructed, as they are in Griffin, Griffin settings already, that you aren't to consider the defendant's refusal to answer the question against him, but--","start":372.026,"stop":381.882,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Fisher, my -- I have a number of problems.","start":381.882,"stop":385.767,"duration":3.88},{"text":"The first is your rule would be seen to be giving noncustodial defendants more rights than those defendants in custody, because you're arguing that -- I think -- that a greater degree of expression other than silence would be needed to show the invocation of the privilege against self-incrimination.","start":385.767,"stop":416.12,"duration":30.35}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":416.12,"stop":416.722,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Or are you trying to equate the rights that a defendant has to custodial and noncustodial with respect to invocation?","start":416.722,"stop":424.209,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":424.209,"stop":424.676,"duration":0.47},{"text":"And I -- and this is where Justice Ginsburg's question came from, so I think it's very important for me to be clear on this.","start":424.676,"stop":429.545,"duration":4.87},{"text":"A person in a noncustodial setting still has fewer rights than a person in a custodial setting.","start":429.545,"stop":434.266,"duration":4.72},{"text":"What the Court held in Berghuis is that if the defendant wants to exercise his prophylactic right under Miranda to cut off police questioning -- those are the words this Court used -- that has to be expressly invoked in some manner during the interrogation.","start":434.266,"stop":447.591,"duration":13.32}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"The problem -- I have an easier problem understanding this argument with respect -- and I'm going to ask your adversaries -- with respect to the situation in which someone is approached by the police and said, come in and talk to us.","start":447.591,"stop":461.584,"duration":13.99},{"text":"I have a hard time understanding how the refusal to come talk to them could be held against them.","start":461.584,"stop":468.655,"duration":7.07},{"text":"There I understand it.","start":468.655,"stop":472.122,"duration":3.47},{"text":"But here, your defendant went in and talked.","start":472.122,"stop":475.426,"duration":3.3},{"text":"So once he chose to do that, why does he get more rights than Berghuis did, who remained silent for 2-1/2 hours?","start":475.426,"stop":486.949,"duration":11.52},{"text":"The Court wasn't willing to find that that was an invocation of the privilege against self-incrimination.","start":486.949,"stop":494.555,"duration":7.61},{"text":"Why would it find the refusal to ask one -- answer one question indicative of the privilege against silence -- or the privilege for silence?","start":494.555,"stop":505.78,"duration":11.22}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"If I may, let me focus on the Berghuis question and then turn to the selective silence point.","start":505.78,"stop":511.349,"duration":5.57},{"text":"The reason why he doesn't have -- Mr. Salinas doesn't have the right that Mr. Berghuis had to cut off questioning.","start":511.349,"stop":517.42,"duration":6.07},{"text":"That's the right that has to be expressly invoked, and it indeed can only be effectuated in this setting.","start":517.42,"stop":522.991,"duration":5.57},{"text":"There was no issue in Berghuis, I don't think, that his silence could be used against him.","start":522.991,"stop":527.526,"duration":4.53},{"text":"The State never argued in the Berghuis case that because he failed to answer for 2 hours that shows he's guilty.","start":527.526,"stop":533.513,"duration":5.99},{"text":"What the State argued in Berghuis was the fact that he later confessed is what shows that he is guilty.","start":533.513,"stop":538.084,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want -- are you saying that before the Miranda warning is required, you cannot invoke the Fifth Amendment?","start":538.084,"stop":545.905,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":545.905,"stop":547.273,"duration":1.37},{"text":"You can.","start":547.273,"stop":547.94,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean -- that's my -- that's how I understood that.","start":547.94,"stop":550.391,"duration":2.45},{"text":"I know you're not arguing that, but that's why I'm--","start":550.391,"stop":551.408,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me separate two rights.","start":551.408,"stop":554.26,"duration":2.85},{"text":"One is the prophylactic right under Miranda to have police cease asking you questions.","start":554.26,"stop":559.58,"duration":5.32},{"text":"That's one right, and that right has to be expressly invoked in some manner during the interrogation, after you've been warned in order to effectuate it.","start":559.58,"stop":567.103,"duration":7.52},{"text":"There is a separate right, which is the genuine Fifth Amendment right to remain silent.","start":567.103,"stop":572.222,"duration":5.12},{"text":"And this Court said in Miranda itself and it's never questioned since that that right doesn't have to be expressly invoked.","start":572.222,"stop":578.578,"duration":6.36},{"text":"So the question is--","start":578.578,"stop":579.494,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, but it can be invoked, and that might make a big difference.","start":579.494,"stop":582.696,"duration":3.2},{"text":"In your -- in your brief, you acknowledge that most citizens know they have a Fifth Amendment right.","start":582.696,"stop":587.148,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":587.148,"stop":587.6,"duration":0.45},{"text":"So I think, Justice Kennedy--","start":587.6,"stop":588.467,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And so if there's -- if questions are somehow troublesome, you say, I'm invoking my Fifth Amendment right; go away, even if you're not in custody, even if Miranda doesn't apply.","start":588.467,"stop":595.587,"duration":7.12}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":595.587,"stop":596.037,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And your client didn't do that here.","start":596.037,"stop":597.222,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"He didn't.","start":597.222,"stop":597.939,"duration":0.72},{"text":"And so the question -- I think unless the Court's prepared to hold that even an expressed invocation could be used against him, then it reduce to the question you framed, Justice Kennedy.","start":597.939,"stop":606.995,"duration":9.06},{"text":"And so, ask yourself whether there's any good reason to require an express invocation in that setting.","start":606.995,"stop":612.549,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Mr. Salinas, remember, did expressly invoke his right to -- Fifth Amendment right to remain silent, at trial in a timely manner, asking for the evidence to be excluded.","start":612.549,"stop":621.571,"duration":9.02},{"text":"So the question is whether there's a reason to ask him to do it sooner.","start":621.571,"stop":624.957,"duration":3.39},{"text":"And our argument is it's unnecessary, unfair, and a rule like that would be unadministrable.","start":624.957,"stop":631.027,"duration":6.07},{"text":"So let me walk through those if I can.","start":631.027,"stop":632.295,"duration":1.27},{"text":"It's unnecessary because all the cases the Solicitor General cites for an express invocation principle involve a scenario where the Government has no good reason to know that it's seeking incriminatory information.","start":632.295,"stop":644.436,"duration":12.14},{"text":"And, Justice Breyer, this is the limiting principle that you were searching for in the tax cases and the like.","start":644.436,"stop":649.305,"duration":4.87},{"text":"If the Government doesn't know or have good reason to know that the defendant who is silent is likely to be exercising his rights, then the Government needs to be put on notice, because the Government may -- may well challenge, may well go seek a court order.","start":649.305,"stop":662.065,"duration":12.76},{"text":"It may well decide to grant immunity.","start":662.065,"stop":663.765,"duration":1.7},{"text":"It may do a number of things.","start":663.765,"stop":664.85,"duration":1.09},{"text":"But here, the Government would do absolutely nothing different.","start":664.85,"stop":667.886,"duration":3.04},{"text":"Police would have done absolutely nothing different.","start":667.886,"stop":669.702,"duration":1.82},{"text":"Indeed, look at the record in this case.","start":669.702,"stop":671.92,"duration":2.22},{"text":"What the Solicitor General says is that Mr. Salinas should have said,","start":671.92,"stop":675.555,"duration":3.63},{"text":"\"I refuse to answer that question. \"","start":675.555,"stop":677.741,"duration":2.19},{"text":"and if he had said that everything would be different.","start":677.741,"stop":680.359,"duration":2.62},{"text":"But look at what the State argued at trial and what the officer testified.","start":680.359,"stop":683.745,"duration":3.39},{"text":"The officer testified: When we asked him that question, he wouldn't answer.","start":683.745,"stop":687.513,"duration":3.77},{"text":"The prosecution argued to the jury: He refused to answer that question.","start":687.513,"stop":691.084,"duration":3.57},{"text":"So there is no ambiguity in the setting whether he was remaining silent.","start":691.084,"stop":695.136,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes, there's no doubt he was remaining silent, but the issue is whether he was trying to raise his Fifth Amendment right.","start":695.136,"stop":702.29,"duration":7.15},{"text":"Now, suppose your rule were, whatever the situation, where either the individual expressly raises his right or at the least it's a fair implication from the circumstance that he was trying to assert his right, would that be a sensible rule?","start":702.29,"stop":722.436,"duration":20.15},{"text":"And if so, how would your case stack up?","start":722.436,"stop":724.988,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":724.988,"stop":725.522,"duration":0.53},{"text":"I think as long as the latter part of that test, Justice Breyer -- can be satisfied by exercising the right, that is remaining silent--","start":725.522,"stop":732.994,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Depends on the circumstance.","start":732.994,"stop":734.594,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--in a setting in which -- in a setting in which the Government has every good reason to know that the person is most likely to be relying on the Fifth Amendment.","start":734.594,"stop":742.767,"duration":8.17},{"text":"And here, where they are investigating a murder and bringing in somebody as a suspect and asking him basically did you commit the crime, I think it's a fair assumption -- at least absent any clarification by the police -- remember, when he was silent, the police would have had every right to say, Mr. Salinas, why aren't you answering the question?","start":742.767,"stop":762.93,"duration":20.16},{"text":"And so the police could clarify.","start":762.93,"stop":763.48,"duration":0.55},{"text":"But absent any clarification from either the police or the suspect, the more likely than not scenario -- and that's the test the Solicitor General agrees should be used -- the more likely than not conclusion there is that he is exercising the right.","start":763.48,"stop":777.273,"duration":13.79},{"text":"Now--","start":777.273,"stop":777.923,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"How would you deal with another comment situation where a defendant meets up with the police, gives a story, and then later changes the story.","start":777.923,"stop":788.415,"duration":10.49},{"text":"And the question is asked at trial, you never volunteered that story to the police when they questioned you.","start":788.415,"stop":797.52,"duration":9.11},{"text":"Would that be silence, to you?","start":797.52,"stop":799.703,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Would that be an invocation of his right not to incriminate himself, or would you -- would the prosecutor be barred from arguing to the jury, as often is done, he chose to say this but not that, so this is a made-up story.","start":799.703,"stop":814.213,"duration":14.51}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, Justice Sotomayor, for two reasons.","start":814.213,"stop":816.732,"duration":2.52},{"text":"One is, if I understood your hypothetical, it sounded like the defendant may have been on the stand and that would be an impeachment scenario that's entirely different.","start":816.732,"stop":822.486,"duration":5.75},{"text":"But even--","start":822.486,"stop":823.102,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Though sometimes they come back and later do a different confession.","start":823.102,"stop":825.421,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":825.421,"stop":825.988,"duration":0.57},{"text":"So but -- but even if that were the case, then that would be basically using his statement against him.","start":825.988,"stop":830.158,"duration":4.17},{"text":"And so a material omission from a statement is not the same as silence.","start":830.158,"stop":834.277,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Here, Mr. Salinas was silent.","start":834.277,"stop":836.728,"duration":2.45},{"text":"Now, it's also not just that there's no good reason to require some sort of magic words to be spoken by the suspect, but it's unfair.","start":836.728,"stop":839.18,"duration":2.45},{"text":"Remember, the States tell you in their amicus brief that if you affirm in this case and adopt the rule they're asking you for, police officers are going to tell people in its custody, which would be nothing more than an accurate statement of the law, sir, if you are silent in response to any of our questions, the prosecution is going to argue that that -- that shows that you're guilty.","start":839.18,"stop":865.331,"duration":26.15},{"text":"They're also going to have every good reason to bring people in.","start":865.331,"stop":868.45,"duration":3.12},{"text":"I think this goes a little bit to Justice Kennedy's question and -- and perhaps just yours as well, the fact that Mr. Salinas did agree to commence this interview.","start":868.45,"stop":876.354,"duration":7.9},{"text":"Remember, he agreed--","start":876.354,"stop":877.472,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He's not in custody.","start":877.472,"stop":879.188,"duration":1.72},{"text":"So let's say he's answering the questions.","start":879.188,"stop":883.209,"duration":4.02},{"text":"All of a sudden he gets a particular question and he says, you know, it's getting late.","start":883.209,"stop":885.392,"duration":2.18},{"text":"I think I'm done and going to go home.","start":885.392,"stop":886.911,"duration":1.52},{"text":"Is that an invocation of the Fifth Amendment right?","start":886.911,"stop":890.196,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think you'd have to ask that to the Solicitor General.","start":890.196,"stop":894.148,"duration":3.95},{"text":"I don't -- I'm not the one requiring an invocation.","start":894.148,"stop":895.2,"duration":1.05},{"text":"And that is part of the administrability problem that the rule raises.","start":895.2,"stop":898.969,"duration":3.77},{"text":"I have no idea of all the permutations, one of which you've raised--","start":898.969,"stop":903.004,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that something--","start":903.004,"stop":903.873,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--but you can imagine many more.","start":903.873,"stop":904.806,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Is that something that could be used against him at trial?","start":904.806,"stop":907.158,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"It can be introduced.","start":907.158,"stop":910.694,"duration":3.54},{"text":"It's hard to understand how that is probative, the fact that he said, I have to leave now.","start":910.694,"stop":915.43,"duration":4.74},{"text":"It's time to go.","start":915.43,"stop":916.38,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's probative if that he says that -- he's answering all the questions, they're fine, all of a sudden they say, well, is your shotgun going to match the shell?","start":916.38,"stop":921.417,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":921.417,"stop":921.884,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Then he goes, gosh, it's late.","start":921.884,"stop":922.684,"duration":0.8},{"text":"I'm going to go home.","start":922.684,"stop":923.267,"duration":0.58},{"text":"That seems as--","start":923.267,"stop":924.053,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":924.053,"stop":925.153,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That seems as probative as the silence.","start":925.153,"stop":926.905,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well -- and so -- what the State cannot do is what it did in this case, and sort of transform that into he refused to answer and therefore it shows he's guilty.","start":926.905,"stop":936.344,"duration":9.44},{"text":"And if I could go back to the part of the unfairness and the difficulty here, it's not -- it's just that -- yes, Mr. Salinas did come to the police station, but remember why he came to the police station, because they said, we want to bring you in to clear you as a suspect, to get elimination prints.","start":936.344,"stop":952.354,"duration":16.01},{"text":"So he was effectively told to come in so that we can clear you as a suspect, asked perfectly innocuous questions at the beginning of the interview, and then everything shifted on a dime to this one “ gotcha ” question.","start":952.354,"stop":964.261,"duration":11.91},{"text":"And I think it's perfectly reasonable and customary in out-of-court settings where the defendant isn't on the stand and so telling some story now trying to backtrack it, but out of court, to be able to selectively exercise your right to silence when you feel now law enforcement is turning against me.","start":964.261,"stop":981.29,"duration":17.03},{"text":"And remember -- this is the other part about, Justice Kennedy, your question.","start":981.29,"stop":987.027,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Of course, people know they have a right to remain silent, so why not -- why not ask them to invoke it.","start":987.027,"stop":993.031,"duration":6},{"text":"Remember, people in this setting generally don't have lawyers.","start":993.031,"stop":996.983,"duration":3.95},{"text":"They don't have a right to lawyers.","start":996.983,"stop":998.001,"duration":1.02},{"text":"What does the layperson know?","start":998.001,"stop":999.917,"duration":1.92},{"text":"The layperson knows, I have a right to remain silent.","start":999.917,"stop":1002.869,"duration":2.95},{"text":"That's what the layperson knows.","start":1002.869,"stop":1004.905,"duration":2.04},{"text":"The layperson doesn't know I have to say some sort of magic words.","start":1004.905,"stop":1008.19,"duration":3.29},{"text":"And the police, believe me, aren't going to tell him that he does in order to--","start":1008.19,"stop":1012.159,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But you draw a distinction between Mr. Salinas's situation and someone who's questioned in the home -- in the person's home or on the street?","start":1012.159,"stop":1019.498,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, I don't think there is a relevant distinction there, Justice Alito, as long as an investigatory interview -- and this Court has said time and again, whether it's Berkemer in a traffic stop or plenty -- or Royer, that the police can try to initiate consensual encounters.","start":1019.498,"stop":1036.127,"duration":16.63},{"text":"And the Court has said time and again that people don't have to participate in them and they can cut them off at any time.","start":1036.127,"stop":1041.994,"duration":5.87},{"text":"And it would be odd--","start":1041.994,"stop":1042.813,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And what if -- what if the person -- what if the person was totally unknown to the police, but called up the police and said they want -- and wants to talk to them for some purpose.","start":1042.813,"stop":1052.969,"duration":10.16},{"text":"You wouldn't draw a distinction between that situation?","start":1052.969,"stop":1056.254,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--In -- well, if he wants to talk to them--","start":1056.254,"stop":1060.242,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He wants to talk to them and--","start":1060.242,"stop":1061.492,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm not sure he has the right to remain silent, no.","start":1061.492,"stop":1064.444,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--He wants to talk to them, and then in the course of this conversation, the same thing happens that happened here.","start":1064.444,"stop":1067.729,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that might, depending on the precision of the hypothetical, be a little bit of a difficult -- different case.","start":1067.729,"stop":1074.05,"duration":6.32},{"text":"But if the person said, I want to talk to you about criminal activity, started giving statements about a -- about a past crime, so it was an investigatory interview, I think it may well apply.","start":1074.05,"stop":1084.107,"duration":10.06}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"You're -- you're giving us Miranda, not Miranda, custody, not custody, gray area.","start":1084.107,"stop":1089.159,"duration":5.05},{"text":"That -- that's what you're arguing.","start":1089.159,"stop":1091.744,"duration":2.58},{"text":"You want a gray area opinion to be written.","start":1091.744,"stop":1093.629,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't want a gray area opinion.","start":1093.629,"stop":1095.998,"duration":2.37},{"text":"Remember, Justice Kennedy, at least the Solicitor General -- and I'll let the State speak for itself -- but the Solicitor General agrees that Griffin rule applies in a noncustodial setting.","start":1095.998,"stop":1103.819,"duration":7.82},{"text":"I -- I totally understand there's a bright line between custody and noncustody, and so a custodial suspect is in a different situation than a noncustodial suspect.","start":1103.819,"stop":1112.108,"duration":8.29},{"text":"But all I'm saying is, again, in agreement with the Solicitor General, whereas all we disagree on is whether the magic words need to be spoken, that a person who is at least in a police investigatory setting and so the police would reasonably expect that a failure to speak or answering your question was relying on a Fifth Amendment--","start":1112.108,"stop":1130.838,"duration":18.73}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm assuming, now that I'm thinking about your argument, you would argue that even in a custodial setting a prosecutor couldn't say, I asked him did he shoot his wife, and the prosecutor can't argue that because he refused to answer that makes him guilty.","start":1130.838,"stop":1148.883,"duration":18.05}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's precisely what the Court said already in Footnote 37 in Miranda, what the lower courts have depended on for a generation now, and I don't think my opponents are even arguing to the contrary.","start":1148.883,"stop":1159.238,"duration":10.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in fact, at most trials, district court judges tell juries the evidence is not the unanswered question, it's the question plus the answer.","start":1159.238,"stop":1168.711,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1168.711,"stop":1168.994,"duration":0.28},{"text":"Fair enough.","start":1168.994,"stop":1169.879,"duration":0.88},{"text":"I think that's perfectly well-established law.","start":1169.879,"stop":1171.846,"duration":1.97},{"text":"And so the reason is, is there any reason to distinguish for purposes of the Griffin rule.","start":1171.846,"stop":1176.8,"duration":4.95},{"text":"I understand those reasons to distinguish in the -- in the settings that Berghuis raises, but for purposes of the Griffin rule, is there any reason to distinguish between a custodial and a noncustodial setting?","start":1176.8,"stop":1187.091,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1187.091,"stop":1187.475,"duration":0.38},{"text":"Well, but yes.","start":1187.475,"stop":1188.175,"duration":0.7},{"text":"The answer is going to be yes, because we're going to hear it in one minute, because, as you say, it follows a fortiori for Berghuis.","start":1188.175,"stop":1194.328,"duration":6.15},{"text":"If you're going to have to make an explicit statement to invoke your Fifth Amendment right when you're not in an inherently coercive setting, I mean, that's going to be the argument.","start":1194.328,"stop":1202.684,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but -- but--","start":1202.684,"stop":1203.184,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"You're not in an inherently coercive setting as you are in the Miranda situation, you're not at trial, and outside those two situations, you have to say explicitly, I'm invoking the Fifth Amendment--","start":1203.184,"stop":1213.206,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":1213.206,"stop":1213.575,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--or tap on the Constitution or something in order to indicate--","start":1213.575,"stop":1216.325,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1216.325,"stop":1216.86,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--that's what's at issue and that's what--","start":1216.86,"stop":1217.894,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Breyer, this is crucial.","start":1217.894,"stop":1219.144,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1219.144,"stop":1219.877,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"If Mr. Salinas had been in a -- if everything about the case was identical, but he'd been in custody, there would be no argument that his silence could be used against him.","start":1219.877,"stop":1228.683,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1228.683,"stop":1229.066,"duration":0.38},{"text":"And that's saying because there we have a line.","start":1229.066,"stop":1230.702,"duration":1.64},{"text":"It's called the in custody line.","start":1230.702,"stop":1232.202,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Once you get outside of custody--","start":1232.202,"stop":1233.737,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's not because of the physical or inherent pressures of custody, because what the Court has said time and again is that after somebody receives their Miranda warnings, they have a free and deliberate choice whether to talk.","start":1233.737,"stop":1245.461,"duration":11.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I don't want to make the Government's argument for them.","start":1245.461,"stop":1247.579,"duration":2.12},{"text":"They'll make it very well.","start":1247.579,"stop":1248.846,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no, but I do want -- I do want to make sure that the Court understands the critical difference between the express invocation requirement that this Court established in Berghuis and what I'm asking for today.","start":1248.846,"stop":1261.487,"duration":12.64},{"text":"And the express invocation requirement in Berghuis is the -- is -- is to administer the Miranda prophylactic rule that the police have to stop asking somebody questions when they invoke their rights.","start":1261.487,"stop":1275.231,"duration":13.74},{"text":"The rights they've just been advised of, remember.","start":1275.231,"stop":1277.933,"duration":2.7},{"text":"It didn't hold in Berghuis and it -- and it's never held that if somebody is Mirandized, and let's say Mr. Berghuis was Mirandized and just remained silent for two hours, and then the police said to themselves, oh, this guy is never going to talk.","start":1277.933,"stop":1291.692,"duration":13.76},{"text":"We end the interview.","start":1291.692,"stop":1292.575,"duration":0.88},{"text":"There would have been no argument the State could have made in that case, that his silence could be used against him.","start":1292.575,"stop":1298.096,"duration":5.52},{"text":"And so I understand that -- that, you know, I'm -- that custody is different, but in terms of the express invocation requirement, there's no express invocation requirement in custody and there's no reason for it here.","start":1298.096,"stop":1310.237,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So I think the argument will be, I think, at least in my mind, that if after sitting there for 45 minutes -- or maybe it was an hour and 45 minutes -- without saying anything, I'm -- I'm maybe taking a dissenting position, but if when the answer doesn't answer over that long period of time, but doesn't say, I want to remain silent, if that long period of behavior is insufficient without the express statement to show that he wanted to remain silent, so outside custodial setting, should it be insufficient to simply remain silent to show that -- you see, it's argument by analogy, I think--","start":1310.237,"stop":1355.783,"duration":45.55}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand, but his silence wasn't able to be used against him in Berghuis; his state -- his later statements were.","start":1355.783,"stop":1361.936,"duration":6.15},{"text":"And so yes, you could have a scenario--","start":1361.936,"stop":1364.621,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't the -- isn't the point, Mr. Fisher--","start":1364.621,"stop":1366.156,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--Pardon?","start":1366.156,"stop":1366.773,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--The question is: What is it insufficient for?","start":1366.773,"stop":1368.942,"duration":2.17},{"text":"In Berghuis, it was insufficient for the purpose of cutting off police questions.","start":1368.942,"stop":1373.394,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1373.394,"stop":1373.71,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not the case here.","start":1373.71,"stop":1375.446,"duration":1.74},{"text":"The question here is whether it's sufficient or insufficient for the purpose of allowing his statement -- his silence to be used against him at trial.","start":1375.446,"stop":1383.868,"duration":8.42}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":1383.868,"stop":1384.618,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"That's an entirely different question, isn't it?","start":1384.618,"stop":1386.154,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly my point.","start":1386.154,"stop":1387.837,"duration":1.68},{"text":"And remember, again, the layperson in this setting who knows -- if there's one thing the layperson knows, and most every American knows this, they have a right to remain silent.","start":1387.837,"stop":1397.193,"duration":9.36},{"text":"So somebody nervous in this setting, without a lawyer, the one sanctuary they have is simply not to talk.","start":1397.193,"stop":1404.448,"duration":7.26},{"text":"If you issue an opinion that says, as the Solicitor General would like, you have to pronounce some sort of magic words, it's terribly unfair and terribly misleading, and again, for no good reason.","start":1404.448,"stop":1414.904,"duration":10.46},{"text":"And it raises all kinds of administrability problems.","start":1414.904,"stop":1418.273,"duration":3.37},{"text":"The Court is going to have an absolute, I think, flood of cases of all the permutations of somebody under different kind of police warnings or the other that may be given ahead of time and different kind of verbal formulations.","start":1418.273,"stop":1431.266,"duration":12.99},{"text":"Maybe he says, I'd like to talk about something else.","start":1431.266,"stop":1434.385,"duration":3.12},{"text":"Maybe he says, as the Chief Justice explained, I'm going to leave now.","start":1434.385,"stop":1438.92,"duration":4.54},{"text":"Maybe he actually just doesn't show up for the interview.","start":1438.92,"stop":1442.055,"duration":3.13},{"text":"There is innumerable permutations.","start":1442.055,"stop":1443.74,"duration":1.68},{"text":"The easy rule--","start":1443.74,"stop":1445.358,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless you're going to argue that -- that silence cannot be -- can never be commented on in any noncustodial situation, and I didn't think you were willing to go that far when I was questioning you previously, you're going to have the same kind of line-drawing questions; aren't you?","start":1445.358,"stop":1463.07,"duration":17.71}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":1463.07,"stop":1463.704,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Where was it held?","start":1463.704,"stop":1464.97,"duration":1.27},{"text":"What was the nature?","start":1464.97,"stop":1466.939,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Who initiated it?","start":1466.939,"stop":1468.106,"duration":1.17},{"text":"Was the person really under suspicion?","start":1468.106,"stop":1470.308,"duration":2.2},{"text":"What was the purpose of the -- of the questioning?","start":1470.308,"stop":1473.693,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"So as to where you draw the line, if I understand your question, as to where an express invocation before trial would be required, you are going to have to draw a line.","start":1473.693,"stop":1482.632,"duration":8.94},{"text":"I think it's very easy to draw the line and just say a police investigatory interview, because that's the setting where the police have every reason to believe that silence is an exercise of the right.","start":1482.632,"stop":1492.923,"duration":10.29},{"text":"All the other settings, whether they be tax settings, whether they be immigration cases, all the totally disparate settings the Solicitor General cites cases involving, it's perfectly reasonable to require an advance indication there.","start":1492.923,"stop":1504.981,"duration":12.06},{"text":"But remember, the Court said in Chavez that the Fifth Amendment is a trial right, and so invoking it at trial is perfectly timely in the ordinary setting.","start":1504.981,"stop":1515.687,"duration":10.71},{"text":"The only question is whether you should have some sort of special requirement for special reason.","start":1515.687,"stop":1519.991,"duration":4.3},{"text":"We think there is no good reason and it would be very unfair.","start":1519.991,"stop":1522.442,"duration":2.45},{"text":"I'd like to--","start":1522.442,"stop":1523.108,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I guess, as I understand your rule -- I'm sorry.","start":1523.108,"stop":1525.31,"duration":2.2},{"text":"I'll ask it on rebuttal.","start":1525.31,"stop":1527.177,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1527.177,"stop":1527.846,"duration":0.67},{"text":"Mr. Curry.","start":1527.846,"stop":1533.314,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1533.314,"stop":1537.885,"duration":4.57},{"text":"Absent an invocation, a defendant's failure to answer a question during a noncustodial, voluntary interview should not be protected by the Fifth Amendment.","start":1537.885,"stop":1546.474,"duration":8.59},{"text":"It should be--","start":1546.474,"stop":1548.974,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But why, counsel?","start":1548.974,"stop":1550.176,"duration":1.2},{"text":"I mean, really what you're saying is, merely because I asked you the question and you choose not to answer it makes you guilty.","start":1550.176,"stop":1557.83,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":1557.83,"stop":1559.448,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- no problem.","start":1559.448,"stop":1562.334,"duration":2.89},{"text":"Here you're asking about the crime of investigation.","start":1562.334,"stop":1566.619,"duration":4.28},{"text":"But you could have asked him, did you kill Joe Blow on another street, and if he had remained silent you would be arguing that proves he is guilty, I could introduce that at trial.","start":1566.619,"stop":1575.808,"duration":9.19},{"text":"And you would be arguing it would be sufficient to convict him; that you merely asked the question and he remained silent about it shows his guilty.","start":1575.808,"stop":1585.414,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yeah, I don't know that that would be sufficient to convict him.","start":1585.414,"stop":1587.865,"duration":2.45},{"text":"And that -- that hypothetical might suggest that the probative value of that particular failure to answer a question was less--","start":1587.865,"stop":1596.471,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a little scary to me that an unanswered question is evidence of guilt.","start":1596.471,"stop":1602.458,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":1602.458,"stop":1603.125,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"He is not arguing that the physical response is not admissible.","start":1603.125,"stop":1608.779,"duration":5.65},{"text":"He is just arguing that the mere asking of a question and a failure to answer it, you can't argue as a prosecutor that that shows someone is guilty.","start":1608.779,"stop":1619.652,"duration":10.87}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think one of the things we are asking the Court to do, Justice Sotomayor, is to recognize that silence, certainly as occurred in this case, doesn't always occur in a vacuum.","start":1619.652,"stop":1629.109,"duration":9.46},{"text":"And the defendant's failure to answer this question, accompanied by things that he did along with or contemporaneously with, you know, the shuffling of the feet, the biting of the bottom lip, revealed a guilty conscience on his part.","start":1629.109,"stop":1641.917,"duration":12.81}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would be up to the jury, wouldn't it?","start":1641.917,"stop":1643.369,"duration":1.45},{"text":"The jury might well agree with Justice Sotomayor that it doesn't prove anything that he answered a question, right?","start":1643.369,"stop":1649.773,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1649.773,"stop":1650.256,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"The question is whether you can ask the jury to consider that.","start":1650.256,"stop":1653.991,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1653.991,"stop":1654.458,"duration":0.47},{"text":"I think that's -- I think that's the import of our argument.","start":1654.458,"stop":1657.26,"duration":2.8},{"text":"And we've referenced this Court's language in Baxter to that extent, that a jury can give what weight they wish to give it.","start":1657.26,"stop":1663.081,"duration":5.82},{"text":"But the--","start":1663.081,"stop":1664.033,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Your -- my hypothetical that I posed earlier, if the police call you and say come in for questioning and you ignore them, is that an invocation of the right to silence or not?","start":1664.033,"stop":1675.554,"duration":11.52}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't know that that's an invocation, Your Honor, but I don't know--","start":1675.554,"stop":1678.44,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Why could you argue that that's--","start":1678.44,"stop":1682.744,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Number one, I don't think a prosecutor ever would argue that because that's ambiguous and not probative, and I think -- not probative for someone just to not come in when police offer them a chance to come in.","start":1682.744,"stop":1694.635,"duration":11.89}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--They -- they're arguing what the legal theory of guilt is in that situation.","start":1694.635,"stop":1698.504,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1698.504,"stop":1699.037,"duration":0.53},{"text":"The legal theory of guilt in that situation would be lessened than it is in this case, because there is no -- there is nothing to suggest that that defendant was guilty necessarily because he decided not to show up to the police.","start":1699.037,"stop":1711.078,"duration":12.04},{"text":"But here in this situation, the defendant's failure to answer the question, accompanied by the other things that he did, did reveal a guilty conscience on his part, and it was nothing to reflect that he was trying--","start":1711.078,"stop":1721.702,"duration":10.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1721.702,"stop":1722.252,"duration":0.55},{"text":"So why is it -- would it be admissible that someone decides -- someone comes in and they say, police say to him or her we are investigating this crime, help us.","start":1722.252,"stop":1734.093,"duration":11.84},{"text":"They start asking questions and it's clear from the first question -- there is a waiver of Miranda and from the first question, the first question is, did you kill this person?","start":1734.093,"stop":1744.235,"duration":10.14},{"text":"The guy remains silent, they ask a whole bunch of other questions and he remains silent.","start":1744.235,"stop":1750.471,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Has he invoked his right?","start":1750.471,"stop":1753.923,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't believe he has, Your Honor.","start":1753.923,"stop":1755.106,"duration":1.18},{"text":"I mean if he -- you said he was provided Miranda rights, so maybe they feel he is in custody or not, but--","start":1755.106,"stop":1760.827,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So a prosecutor could go into the jury and say he waived his Miranda rights and he is guilty because he refused to answer our questions?","start":1760.827,"stop":1769.7,"duration":8.87}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--He is guilty if he revealed a guilty conscience, Your Honor.","start":1769.7,"stop":1776.004,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"He wouldn't say that.","start":1776.004,"stop":1776.706,"duration":0.7},{"text":"He would say one of the indications of his guilt is that he refused to answer the question.","start":1776.706,"stop":1783.21,"duration":6.5},{"text":"No prosecutor would argue that that alone would support a conviction, right?","start":1783.21,"stop":1788.097,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct, Your Honor.","start":1788.097,"stop":1788.88,"duration":0.78},{"text":"And that's not what we're -- that's not what we are asking the Court to do here.","start":1788.88,"stop":1791.798,"duration":2.92},{"text":"We're not asking the Court to say that every time silence occurs that's necessarily going to be probative, and every time silence occurs that's necessarily going to be something that we utilize.","start":1791.798,"stop":1800.071,"duration":8.27},{"text":"We're merely saying that in this particular situation the defendant needs to tell something to the police in order to reveal that he is relying on a constitutional right and not merely having--","start":1800.071,"stop":1809.593,"duration":9.52}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":1809.593,"stop":1810.827,"duration":1.23},{"text":"Just to nail that down, because your first three words were “ absent an invocation ”.","start":1810.827,"stop":1816.247,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Your Honor.","start":1816.247,"stop":1817.481,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you now adopting the Solicitor General's argument, because your brief goes further?","start":1817.481,"stop":1822.401,"duration":4.92},{"text":"So are you now saying that the crucial thing is the invocation?","start":1822.401,"stop":1826.555,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that has been our position, Your Honor.","start":1826.555,"stop":1828.639,"duration":2.08},{"text":"We do have some alternative argues as well based upon this Court's jurisprudence.","start":1828.639,"stop":1834.042,"duration":5.4},{"text":"But I think the Government and we both agree that the defendant in this particular situation would need to invoke.","start":1834.042,"stop":1841.231,"duration":7.19},{"text":"And that is the basis upon which we proceed.","start":1841.231,"stop":1844.1,"duration":2.87},{"text":"And we are not proceeding just upon Berghuis v. Thompkins.","start":1844.1,"stop":1846.3,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"And so you would agree with the Government that if he had invoked, that the Fifth Amendment right would come into play.","start":1846.3,"stop":1852.604,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"We would not attempt to just -- we would not attempt to introduce anything, for example “ I plead the Fifth ”,","start":1852.604,"stop":1857.241,"duration":4.64},{"text":"\"I don't want to talk any more. \"","start":1857.241,"stop":1858.541,"duration":1.3},{"text":"something like that.","start":1858.541,"stop":1859.61,"duration":1.07},{"text":"No, we would not be introducing that.","start":1859.61,"stop":1861.126,"duration":1.52},{"text":"I do believe that would be a rule -- a violation of the rule--","start":1861.126,"stop":1866.597,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the line you're drawing, between his just not answering and his saying, I don't want to answer?","start":1866.597,"stop":1873.084,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct, if I understand your question.","start":1873.084,"stop":1876.119,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But the latter can't be introduce to the jury, but the former can.","start":1876.119,"stop":1879.523,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1879.523,"stop":1881.106,"duration":1.58},{"text":"That's the rule--","start":1881.106,"stop":1882.173,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why would you -- why would you draw that -- that line?","start":1882.173,"stop":1884.825,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think, Your Honor, I would not want to -- I would not want to introduce a statement that a defendant was relying on a constitutional right by saying,","start":1884.825,"stop":1894.866,"duration":10.04},{"text":"\"I don't want to talk any more. \"","start":1894.866,"stop":1896.299,"duration":1.43},{"text":"as opposed to the mere silence, which might be probative in conjunction with other evidence.","start":1896.299,"stop":1901.37,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Doesn't the mere silence suggest","start":1901.37,"stop":1903.722,"duration":2.35},{"text":"\"I don't want to talk any more? \"","start":1903.722,"stop":1905.139,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"It might.","start":1905.139,"stop":1906.341,"duration":1.2},{"text":"But it also might suggest that he's having difficulty coming up with an exculpatory response.","start":1906.341,"stop":1911.226,"duration":4.89},{"text":"It might suggest that he can't think of a good answer.","start":1911.226,"stop":1914.16,"duration":2.93},{"text":"It might suggest that he is worried about the question and he is thinking more about how worried he is about the question than how he wants to respond to it.","start":1914.16,"stop":1921.116,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Particularly since he did want to talk some more, right?","start":1921.116,"stop":1923.566,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1923.566,"stop":1924.385,"duration":0.82},{"text":"He continued to respond, you know, several questions thereafter, continuing to provide exculpatory responses.","start":1924.385,"stop":1934.241,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But isn't the most logical inference from the silence not that he isn't quick enough to come up with an exculpatory answer, but that it would incriminate him if he answered?","start":1934.241,"stop":1944.966,"duration":10.72}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1944.966,"stop":1947.584,"duration":2.62},{"text":"That may be -- that may be a permissible inference.","start":1947.584,"stop":1950.703,"duration":3.12},{"text":"But I do not believe that that necessarily means that he was invoking his Fifth Amendment right, because he did continue to talk.","start":1950.703,"stop":1957.023,"duration":6.32},{"text":"He already knew what the police were investigating.","start":1957.023,"stop":1961.325,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But he could -- he could invoke the Fifth Amendment with respect to one set of questions and not another.","start":1961.325,"stop":1968.581,"duration":7.26},{"text":"And what's disturbing me about your position, if it's -- if you have -- someone being interrogated who is savvy will say, “ I plead the Fifth ”.","start":1968.581,"stop":1984.107,"duration":15.53},{"text":"And somebody who is not that smart is just silent.","start":1984.107,"stop":1991.947,"duration":7.84},{"text":"To make a difference between those two people on whether comment can be made on the failure to respond is troublesome.","start":1991.947,"stop":2003.837,"duration":11.89}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I think that would be consistent with this Court's jurisprudence to -- to allow the use of evidence if there was no invocation involved.","start":2003.837,"stop":2014.526,"duration":10.69},{"text":"In Jenkins v. Anderson, Justice Stevens recognized the importance of an invocation, even in -- even in that type of situation.","start":2014.526,"stop":2022.799,"duration":8.27},{"text":"This Court -- it's not just Berghuis v. Thompkins that we're relying upon, where the Court has recognized the necessity of an invocation.","start":2022.799,"stop":2030.988,"duration":8.19},{"text":"Garner v. United States says the same thing, that -- that an invocation is necessary for Fifth Amendment rights.","start":2030.988,"stop":2036.725,"duration":5.74},{"text":"And I know that we don't have a case that is squarely on -- on four with this one.","start":2036.725,"stop":2040.677,"duration":3.95},{"text":"But all the defendant would have to say is, I don't want to talk anymore, or I don't want to answer that question, and then we would be in a completely different posture at this point.","start":2040.677,"stop":2049.616,"duration":8.94},{"text":"But here, the -- the defendant failed to answer a question, and did other things that revealed a guilty conscience on his part, and that is precisely the type of evidence that we believe that we can introduce.","start":2049.616,"stop":2060.007,"duration":10.39}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But, Mr. Curry, in a case like Berghuis, which is in a custodial setting, if the defendant there had not ever said anything, had gone through the entire interview and really never said a word, so that the police kept asking him questions, but he never said anything, the prosecutors could then not go in and say, look, for 3 hours, we asked him questions and he didn't talk.","start":2060.007,"stop":2083.789,"duration":23.78},{"text":"That would be off limits.","start":2083.789,"stop":2085.672,"duration":1.88},{"text":"And the question is, if that's off limits, why shouldn't this be off limits as well?","start":2085.672,"stop":2090.61,"duration":4.94},{"text":"If there's no invocation necessary there, for some of the reasons that Justice Ginsburg was saying, why should there be an invocation requirement here?","start":2090.61,"stop":2099.716,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, number one, because the hypotheticals are different.","start":2099.716,"stop":2103.584,"duration":3.87},{"text":"In -- in our particular situation, the defendant did answer questions, and only did, you know, fail to answer one particular question.","start":2103.584,"stop":2110.024,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2110.024,"stop":2110.34,"duration":0.32},{"text":"I -- I understand that in your case, there happens to be a kind of selective answering sort of question.","start":2110.34,"stop":2116.678,"duration":6.34},{"text":"But let's say -- let's take that out of the picture, all right?","start":2116.678,"stop":2119.545,"duration":2.87},{"text":"And just say, you know, he just didn't want to answer questions, all right?","start":2119.545,"stop":2123.414,"duration":3.87},{"text":"So then the question is, why would that case be any different from the case that I posited?","start":2123.414,"stop":2128.818,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2128.818,"stop":2129.968,"duration":1.15},{"text":"In -- in Berghuis v. Thompkins, this Court looked at the ambiguous nature of whether or not the invocation had occurred.","start":2129.968,"stop":2136.072,"duration":6.1},{"text":"If, in your hypothetical, the defendant failed to answer any questions whatsoever--","start":2136.072,"stop":2139.959,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- he didn't invoke, he just didn't answer.","start":2139.959,"stop":2142.328,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--But it could be a suggestion where he was attempting to exercise the -- the right, because he never answered anything.","start":2142.328,"stop":2147.363,"duration":5.03},{"text":"But in our situation, the defendant can't be said to have been doing that.","start":2147.363,"stop":2151.184,"duration":3.82},{"text":"He can't be said to have been exercising the right because he failed to answer a question, but answered several other questions.","start":2151.184,"stop":2156.469,"duration":5.28}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2156.469,"stop":2157.087,"duration":0.62},{"text":"So you're pinning your argument really on the fact that he did a lot of answering.","start":2157.087,"stop":2159.304,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"That's one of the reasons, Your Honor.","start":2159.304,"stop":2163.574,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"On this -- on this, you know, you can't pick and choose kind of argument.","start":2163.574,"stop":2167.276,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we're saying that you cannot infer an assertion of a Fifth Amendment right based upon this.","start":2167.276,"stop":2173.263,"duration":5.99},{"text":"We cannot infer that he was necessarily asserting his Fifth Amendment right, whether to cut off questioning or stop talking altogether, or, you know--","start":2173.263,"stop":2181.75,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"So would it be fair to say that your argument is, look, you can't just like keep talking and talking and talking and -- and at that point, you have to invoke?","start":2181.75,"stop":2193.157,"duration":11.41},{"text":"If -- if you've been doing a lot of talking and then decide you want to stay silent, at that point, you have to invoke.","start":2193.157,"stop":2199.311,"duration":6.15},{"text":"But that's not to say that you have to invoke in every noncustodial encounter.","start":2199.311,"stop":2204.949,"duration":5.64},{"text":"Is that your argument?","start":2204.949,"stop":2206.151,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":2206.151,"stop":2206.684,"duration":0.53},{"text":"I think you need to invoke in every -- every noncustodial encounter if -- if you do not want the things that you say to be utilized against you.","start":2206.684,"stop":2215.007,"duration":8.32},{"text":"If you -- if you want to -- you know, if you want to be prevented from that evidence being utilized, you have to say, I don't want to talk anymore, or I plead the Fifth, or whatever the words--","start":2215.007,"stop":2224.279,"duration":9.27}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But I thought you said he didn't have to do that if he didn't answer any questions.","start":2224.279,"stop":2228.565,"duration":4.29},{"text":"Didn't you?","start":2228.565,"stop":2229.432,"duration":0.87},{"text":"Isn't that what you said?","start":2229.432,"stop":2231.166,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"You took the words out of my mouth.","start":2231.166,"stop":2232.551,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":2232.551,"stop":2233.134,"duration":0.58},{"text":"No.","start":2233.134,"stop":2234.001,"duration":0.87},{"text":"If he didn't answer any questions, then -- then it would be drawn closer to -- to Berghuis v. Thompkins, in which this--","start":2234.001,"stop":2240.888,"duration":6.89}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but in Berghuis, we found no implication.","start":2240.888,"stop":2244.442,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct.","start":2244.442,"stop":2245.559,"duration":1.12},{"text":"Correct.","start":2245.559,"stop":2246.242,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"So -- so Justice Kagan's question stands.","start":2246.242,"stop":2249.561,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but the defendant in Berghuis did answer some questions, Your Honor, and that's what makes it different from Berghuis.","start":2249.561,"stop":2255.834,"duration":6.27},{"text":"In -- in that -- in that case, the defendant did ultimately--","start":2255.834,"stop":2259.619,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, a few, as I recall.","start":2259.619,"stop":2261.236,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct.","start":2261.236,"stop":2261.619,"duration":0.38},{"text":"He--","start":2261.619,"stop":2262.104,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Curry, Berghuis is different for a different reason.","start":2262.104,"stop":2264.104,"duration":2},{"text":"Berghuis is different because the question in Berghuis is what do you have to do to make the police go away.","start":2264.104,"stop":2270.492,"duration":6.39},{"text":"Here, the police were not going away.","start":2270.492,"stop":2271.659,"duration":1.17},{"text":"There was no -- there's no question of that.","start":2271.659,"stop":2273.545,"duration":1.89},{"text":"But the question is what do you have to do in order to bar the prosecutor from introducing your silence at trial.","start":2273.545,"stop":2280.865,"duration":7.32},{"text":"So that's a really different question, isn't it?","start":2280.865,"stop":2281.599,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, it is a different question, but here, I think the police were, quote-unquote, “ going away ”.","start":2281.599,"stop":2288.638,"duration":7.04},{"text":"I mean, they -- they finished their questioning at some point.","start":2288.638,"stop":2291.59,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":2291.59,"stop":2293.057,"duration":1.47},{"text":"That's why Berghuis is irrelevant here, because Berghuis said at a certain point, you know, you need to invoke in order to stop questioning.","start":2293.057,"stop":2300.446,"duration":7.39},{"text":"But -- but that's not what's at issue here.","start":2300.446,"stop":2303.231,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"But this Court's case law still requires an invocation.","start":2303.231,"stop":2307.017,"duration":3.79},{"text":"And the rule we're asking this Court to adopt would essentially settle the split that largely exists in--","start":2307.017,"stop":2313.17,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What is that?","start":2313.17,"stop":2313.853,"duration":0.68},{"text":"That is what I'm -- I'm uncertain about this.","start":2313.853,"stop":2316.372,"duration":2.52},{"text":"And they cite page 468, note 37 of Miranda.","start":2316.372,"stop":2321.042,"duration":4.67},{"text":"What is the law, in your opinion now, in respect to -- and what case would support this?","start":2321.042,"stop":2327.18,"duration":6.14},{"text":"A defendant comes in, he is warned and given his Miranda rights.","start":2327.18,"stop":2333.084,"duration":5.9},{"text":"He says fine, and then he proceeds to answer a whole bunch of questions.","start":2333.084,"stop":2341.873,"duration":8.79},{"text":"Then they ask question number 432, he says nothing.","start":2341.873,"stop":2343.34,"duration":1.47},{"text":"You then go on to 433, 434, et cetera, and he answers them all.","start":2343.34,"stop":2348.427,"duration":5.09},{"text":"Okay?","start":2348.427,"stop":2349.077,"duration":0.65},{"text":"At the trial, the lawyer -- the prosecutor wants to comment on the fact that in the face of that single question -- though answering many, many more -- he remained silent.","start":2349.077,"stop":2360.567,"duration":11.49},{"text":"Does Griffin say he can -- the prosecutor can make that comment, yes or no?","start":2360.567,"stop":2366.571,"duration":6},{"text":"And I'd appreciate the Government answering this question, too, because they're -- if they -- are they speaking here, or are you doing the whole argument?","start":2366.571,"stop":2374.077,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, the Government is also arguing as well, Your Honor.","start":2374.077,"stop":2376.661,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- I'd like to get the same answer.","start":2376.661,"stop":2378.713,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2378.713,"stop":2379.729,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Because I -- well, now they cite for the proposition, I think, that it -- that the prosecutor is forbidden to make that comment, note 37 of Miranda.","start":2379.729,"stop":2390.021,"duration":10.29},{"text":"Okay.","start":2390.021,"stop":2390.754,"duration":0.73},{"text":"I just read it.","start":2390.754,"stop":2391.705,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2391.705,"stop":2393.405,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And I -- may be ambiguous on the point.","start":2393.405,"stop":2394.907,"duration":1.5},{"text":"It says you have the right to maintain immunity in the face of an accusation.","start":2394.907,"stop":2397.942,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2397.942,"stop":2398.576,"duration":0.63},{"text":"I think the reliance of on the footnote is -- is--","start":2398.576,"stop":2400.426,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, fine.","start":2400.426,"stop":2402.511,"duration":2.09},{"text":"But what's your opinion?","start":2402.511,"stop":2403.93,"duration":1.42},{"text":"I mean, what is the law in respect to that single point?","start":2403.93,"stop":2407.798,"duration":3.87},{"text":"And at least to me, I'd -- I'd like to know your opinion on that.","start":2407.798,"stop":2412.452,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, I do not believe that this Court has extended Griffin to this particular type of fact situation, and Griffin wouldn't apply to that.","start":2412.452,"stop":2418.956,"duration":6.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any authority, or is it just your opinion that we have to go on?","start":2418.956,"stop":2423.475,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I believe this Court would have had the opportunity to extend Griffin.","start":2423.475,"stop":2427.046,"duration":3.57},{"text":"For example, Doyle v. Ohio, basically, the Court did not do that.","start":2427.046,"stop":2430.498,"duration":3.45},{"text":"This Court had the -- the opportunity to extend Griffin in Fletcher v. Weir and did not do that.","start":2430.498,"stop":2435.199,"duration":4.7},{"text":"So I do not believe this Court has necessarily, you know, sought to always attempt to extend Griffin in that situation.","start":2435.199,"stop":2442.221,"duration":7.02},{"text":"Now, we -- I see some ambiguity in the standing mute phrase from footnote 37.","start":2442.221,"stop":2447.423,"duration":5.2},{"text":"Does that mean not talking at all?","start":2447.423,"stop":2449.542,"duration":2.12},{"text":"Does that mean not answering one particular question?","start":2449.542,"stop":2452.161,"duration":2.62},{"text":"In your hypothetical, if it was as probative as it was in our case, you know, that might be something the prosecution would want to use without violating the Fifth Amendment right, because there's no clear indication that the defendant did in fact rely upon his Fifth Amendment right.","start":2452.161,"stop":2464.302,"duration":12.14},{"text":"Now, I don't want to, you know, misread footnote 37, but that's how we read footnote 37, because of the absence of -- there's many, many cases cited there, and it's not clear that it's attempted to apply an -- an extension of Griffin in that situation.","start":2464.302,"stop":2479.911,"duration":15.61},{"text":"The rule we're -- we're offering here would not -- would not change the law with regard to how it exists in much of the Federal Circuits.","start":2479.911,"stop":2490.969,"duration":11.06},{"text":"In much of the Federal Circuits, these defendants where -- where the courts have held that we cannot utilize this evidence, those defendants have in fact done something to invoke.","start":2490.969,"stop":2499.475,"duration":8.51},{"text":"So I think the -- the rule that we're asking the Court to adopt would allow for these -- that case law to stand; i.e., if a defendant says I don't want to talk anymore, I plead the Fifth, you know, we're not asking this Court to issue a rule that says that we can introduce that.","start":2499.475,"stop":2516.019,"duration":16.54},{"text":"All we're asking this Court to -- to introduce is consistent with this Court's case law that would require an invocation, or some invocation that the Fifth Amendment right was being relied upon, and not just a difficulty with the question, or I can't think up an exculpatory answer for that particular question, so I don't know what to say.","start":2516.019,"stop":2537.1,"duration":21.08},{"text":"I mean, there, the defendant is not relying upon a constitutional right.","start":2537.1,"stop":2541.052,"duration":3.95},{"text":"And I think we're asking this Court to -- to look at whether an inference has to be made that the Fifth Amendment right is being done, or perhaps another inference can be -- can be provided.","start":2541.052,"stop":2551.693,"duration":10.64},{"text":"And Baxter v. Palmigiano allows for acquiescence, you know, to -- to be something that we can utilize against a defendant.","start":2551.693,"stop":2560.715,"duration":9.02},{"text":"Here, the jury--","start":2560.715,"stop":2561.998,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Where does the compulsion line come in?","start":2561.998,"stop":2565.084,"duration":3.09},{"text":"Your adversary points out that under this scenario, the police could ask you questions and say to you, you know, if you stay quiet in this question, I'm going to use it against you at trial.","start":2565.084,"stop":2577.76,"duration":12.68},{"text":"That police will actually to that.","start":2577.76,"stop":2580.077,"duration":2.32},{"text":"That they'll actually come in and tell defendants who are telling the story, you know, either answer or it'll be used against you.","start":2580.077,"stop":2590.502,"duration":10.42}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--I could perceive then, Your Honor, the -- the trial court upholding a claim by the defendant that he was coerced at that point, that at that point, the officer--","start":2590.502,"stop":2600.273,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So why can't you say that a call from a police officer to someone who says come in and talk, that that can't be used against them at trial as -- you gave me a different answer.","start":2600.273,"stop":2611.398,"duration":11.13},{"text":"You said it wasn't probative.","start":2611.398,"stop":2612.598,"duration":1.2},{"text":"But you didn't say Griffin would protect that.","start":2612.598,"stop":2615.283,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Alan K. Curry","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":2615.283,"stop":2616.385,"duration":1.1},{"text":"If -- I don't know that I would say Griffin is protecting it, but what I would say is this Court's penalty jurisprudence would say that when a penalty flows directly from something the defendant is, you know, either saying or not saying, you know, that could be a problem.","start":2616.385,"stop":2629.11,"duration":12.72},{"text":"So when an officer says, you know,","start":2629.11,"stop":2630.812,"duration":1.7},{"text":"\"I'm going to hold -- hold against you your failure to answer a question. \"","start":2630.812,"stop":2635.597,"duration":4.79},{"text":"you know, that can be something where the court might utilize as -- as for some sort of penalties flown.","start":2635.597,"stop":2640.584,"duration":4.99},{"text":"Justice -- Justice Stevens said, in his dissenting opinion in McKune v. Lile, that there is an appreciate difference between some sort of sanction, official sanction being placed upon a, you know, of essentially disobeying of an order as opposed to a voluntary choice arising from -- from just a possible adverse consequence.","start":2640.584,"stop":2665.966,"duration":25.38},{"text":"And here, I think, the fact situation that confronts this Court in this case is just the risk of an adverse consequence and not something that necessarily is going to occur.","start":2665.966,"stop":2674.572,"duration":8.61},{"text":"However, if an officer says,","start":2674.572,"stop":2676.674,"duration":2.1},{"text":"\"I'm necessarily going to use this against you. \"","start":2676.674,"stop":2679.725,"duration":3.05},{"text":"the adverse consequence may become more -- more tangible at that point.","start":2679.725,"stop":2683.344,"duration":3.62},{"text":"That isn't the facts of this particular case.","start":2683.344,"stop":2686.981,"duration":3.64},{"text":"I also want to disagree with Mr. Fisher with regard to his suggestion that the police essentially manipulated this.","start":2686.981,"stop":2700.889,"duration":13.91},{"text":"If you look on the Joint Appendix, page 14, lines 9 and 10, the officer clearly says that he wants Mr. Salinas to come down to the police station and talk, as well as do elimination fingerprints.","start":2700.889,"stop":2715.28,"duration":14.39},{"text":"The officer had already been questioned.","start":2715.28,"stop":2718.6,"duration":3.32},{"text":"These people knew we were investigating a double murder.","start":2718.6,"stop":2721.635,"duration":3.04},{"text":"These people knew that they were looking for a shotgun.","start":2721.635,"stop":2724.385,"duration":2.75},{"text":"They now have a shotgun that they got from the defendant.","start":2724.385,"stop":2726.637,"duration":2.25},{"text":"So this defendant was not, you know, all of a sudden sprung on him the idea that they were, you know, looking for him as the possible suspect at that point when they asked a ballistics question.","start":2726.637,"stop":2737.895,"duration":11.26}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":2737.895,"stop":2739.347,"duration":1.45},{"text":"Ms. Anders?","start":2739.347,"stop":2750.286,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":2750.286,"stop":2753.072,"duration":2.79},{"text":"In Minnesota v. Murphy, this Court applied the general rule that the Fifth Amendment privilege is not self-executing and that a suspect must invoke it in order to claim its protection to a noncustodial interview in which the -- the probation officer doing the questioning was aware that the questions that she asked could be incriminating.","start":2753.072,"stop":2772.651,"duration":19.58},{"text":"The Court there held that because the suspect had not invoked his Fifth Amendment rights, his statements could be used against him as evidence at trial.","start":2772.651,"stop":2780.405,"duration":7.75},{"text":"A suspect's silence should similarly be admissible against him when he fails to expressly invoke the privilege.","start":2780.405,"stop":2785.976,"duration":5.57},{"text":"Requiring invocation--","start":2785.976,"stop":2787.495,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That is such a radical position, that silence is an admission of guilty.","start":2787.495,"stop":2793.149,"duration":5.65},{"text":"That's really what the argument is.","start":2793.149,"stop":2795.851,"duration":2.7},{"text":"I certainly understand that speaking can implicate you, and if you choose to speak, clearly whatever you say can be used against you unless you're in custody and unless you've invoke the right before.","start":2795.851,"stop":2810.776,"duration":14.92},{"text":"But this is radically different.","start":2810.776,"stop":2812.943,"duration":2.17},{"text":"We are -- we are -- you're trying to say acts of commission and omission are the same, but statements are different than silence, because then you're making the person who is asking the question your -- your admission.","start":2812.943,"stop":2829.072,"duration":16.13},{"text":"You are saying you're adopting their statement as true.","start":2829.072,"stop":2833.457,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think the Court has repeatedly recognized that when a citizen is voluntarily interacting with the police and there -- there is no coercion because it's not a custodial situation, we expect that person to be treated as fully capable of deciding whether or not to assert his rights.","start":2833.457,"stop":2847.949,"duration":14.49},{"text":"This is what the Court said in United States v. Drayton in an analogous context, which is whether someone has voluntarily consented to a search.","start":2847.949,"stop":2855.889,"duration":7.94},{"text":"The person, even if he is not told that -- that he can refuse to -- to consent, we still assume that he knew that he could refuse to consent, and, therefore, it was a voluntary choice.","start":2855.889,"stop":2866.53,"duration":10.64},{"text":"And I think you can draw the same inference here, that when someone -- we -- I think we all agree that most people know -- people know what their Fifth Amendment rights are, and, therefore, they can assert them when they don't face any coercive pressure.","start":2866.53,"stop":2877.819,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Ms. Anders?","start":2877.819,"stop":2878.671,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"And so when the person does not do that--","start":2878.671,"stop":2880.455,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2880.455,"stop":2880.957,"duration":0.5},{"text":"We don't require invocation at trial, and we don't require invocation in a custodial setting.","start":2880.957,"stop":2887.443,"duration":6.49},{"text":"And you might think, well, custodial, that's very different because, after all, custodial is inherently coercive, but that's the whole point of Miranda warnings, is that once we give Miranda warnings, that coercion is dispelled and the custodial setting essentially becomes like a noncustodial setting.","start":2887.443,"stop":2905.322,"duration":17.88},{"text":"So if we don't require invocation even after Miranda warnings are given in a custodial setting, why should we require invocation here?","start":2905.322,"stop":2915.611,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think the reason that we don't require invocation in the Miranda setting, I think highlights the fundamental difference between custodial interrogation and noncustodial interrogation.","start":2915.611,"stop":2923.949,"duration":8.34},{"text":"So in the custodial setting, the Court has said that -- that the suspect faces inherent coercive pressures to confess--","start":2923.949,"stop":2930.603,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because then when--","start":2930.603,"stop":2931.389,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--and therefore--","start":2931.389,"stop":2932.005,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--you're given the warnings, and then that's gone.","start":2932.005,"stop":2933.122,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Exactly.","start":2933.122,"stop":2933.839,"duration":0.72},{"text":"That's why we give the warnings.","start":2933.839,"stop":2934.591,"duration":0.75},{"text":"And in the warnings, we promise the suspect that his silence will not be used against him.","start":2934.591,"stop":2939.209,"duration":4.62},{"text":"And so this is what the Court said in Doyle v. Ohio, that because of that promise, the suspect does not have to expressly invoke, and his silence can't be used against him.","start":2939.209,"stop":2946.565,"duration":7.36},{"text":"But in the voluntary situation, we presume that the suspect knows his rights, and because he is not facing any pressure, he can simply say,","start":2946.565,"stop":2954.553,"duration":7.99},{"text":"\"I don't want to answer that question. \"","start":2954.553,"stop":2956.505,"duration":1.95},{"text":"And so when he doesn't say that--","start":2956.505,"stop":2958.207,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You've -- you've said in your brief that there might be a whole other -- many other reasons for remaining silent, and I -- I suggested that the -- in -- in this kind of scenario, the most likely reason that the suspect will clam up is that he fears incrimination.","start":2958.207,"stop":2988.742,"duration":30.54},{"text":"But what -- what obvious other reasons unrelated to the Fifth Amendment why a defendant might remain silent?","start":2988.742,"stop":2997.432,"duration":8.69},{"text":"I mean, the Griffin rule is he doesn't have to say “ I plead the Fifth ” because we assume that when he doesn't take the stand he is doing so because he doesn't want to incriminate himself.","start":2997.432,"stop":3011.174,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's right.","start":3011.174,"stop":3012.341,"duration":1.17},{"text":"The -- the Griffin rule says -- or it's premised on the idea that when you fail to testify at trial you're inherently exercising your Fifth Amendment right.","start":3012.341,"stop":3019.863,"duration":7.52},{"text":"But I think when you're looking at a -- a noncustodial interrogation, the question whether the person is trying to exercise his Fifth Amendment right, I think the operative question is not whether he wants to avoid inculpating himself, it's whether he wants to refuse to answer as a matter of right.","start":3019.863,"stop":3035.123,"duration":15.26},{"text":"And I think we know that because, if you look at the interview as a whole, presumably his overarching motivation is not to inculpate himself.","start":3035.123,"stop":3042.794,"duration":7.67},{"text":"That's why his statement -- his statements can be used against him at trial, because those statements we -- we've -- the Court held in Minnesota v. Murphy, those statements are inconsistent with a desire to refuse to answer as a matter of right.","start":3042.794,"stop":3055.87,"duration":13.08}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So are you -- are you conceding the -- the point that they make?","start":3055.87,"stop":3058.155,"duration":2.29},{"text":"I -- that -- that even if in the custodial setting he waives his Miranda right.","start":3058.155,"stop":3063.274,"duration":5.12},{"text":"He answers 500 questions, but doesn't answer one of the 500, that the prosecutor cannot comment on that fact that he didn't answer that one?","start":3063.274,"stop":3072.313,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that raises a--","start":3072.313,"stop":3073.415,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it?","start":3073.415,"stop":3078.117,"duration":4.7},{"text":"What do you think?","start":3078.117,"stop":3074.765,"duration":-3.35},{"text":"He says, “ No, you can't ”, and he quotes Miranda.","start":3074.765,"stop":3077.367,"duration":2.6},{"text":"Okay.","start":3077.367,"stop":3078.986,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, there is -- there is a circuit split on that, and -- and I think the circuit split shows that it raises a different analytical question that the Court doesn't have to get into here.","start":3078.986,"stop":3085.556,"duration":6.57},{"text":"The circuit split is that some courts say, as I understand it, that even after the person waives his Miranda rights, Doyle still applies, and so you can't use his silence against him.","start":3085.556,"stop":3094.578,"duration":9.02},{"text":"And some of those other courts say, no, once he has waived his Miranda rights, he is essentially in the same situation as he would be if he weren't in custody--","start":3094.578,"stop":3101.749,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And do you have a view on it?","start":3101.749,"stop":3102.684,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--I -- I think we think that the better view is that Doyle probably does not apply, but I think there is a serious question there.","start":3102.684,"stop":3108.588,"duration":5.9},{"text":"And I think the Court doesn't have to resolve it here because, again, that highlights a distinction between custodial and noncustodial interrogation, that once the suspect has been promised--","start":3108.588,"stop":3118.194,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what is your answer to Justice Kagan's earlier question to the hypothetical of the defendant that says nothing for 20 questions?","start":3118.194,"stop":3128.832,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I -- I think the standard--","start":3128.832,"stop":3130.168,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Then there's no -- and there's no Miranda warning and no custody.","start":3130.168,"stop":3132.37,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":3132.37,"stop":3132.97,"duration":0.6},{"text":"So like this case except 20 questions.","start":3132.97,"stop":3134.905,"duration":1.94},{"text":"Well, I think the standard is whether the -- the suspect has done something that reasonably can be construed as invocation.","start":3134.905,"stop":3140.809,"duration":5.9},{"text":"This is the standard that the Court announced in United States v. Quinn a long time ago, but it's also the same formulation that the Court used in Davis and Berghuis.","start":3140.809,"stop":3148.713,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what does that mean?","start":3148.713,"stop":3149.23,"duration":0.52},{"text":"Does he just -- how about if he just said,","start":3149.23,"stop":3150.932,"duration":1.7},{"text":"\"You know, I don't really want to answer that question? \"","start":3150.932,"stop":3152.7,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"I think if he expresses the desire not to answer the question, that is sufficient because he is saying,","start":3152.7,"stop":3157.569,"duration":4.87},{"text":"\"I'm not going to answer that. \"","start":3157.569,"stop":3158.771,"duration":1.2},{"text":"and implicitly he has a right not to do that.","start":3158.771,"stop":3161.154,"duration":2.38},{"text":"I think the 20 questions hypothetical that Justice Kennedy proposed, probably that would not be sufficient by -- by analogy to Thompkins where the suspect sat silent for two hours.","start":3161.154,"stop":3170.661,"duration":9.51}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":3170.661,"stop":3171.161,"duration":0.5},{"text":"But -- but I don't think you -- you were going to tell me this great deal of conduct, what silence could mean other than “ I fear incrimination ”.","start":3171.161,"stop":3184.219,"duration":13.06},{"text":"What else is--","start":3184.219,"stop":3186.188,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":3186.188,"stop":3186.605,"duration":0.42},{"text":"I think -- I think there are several types -- there are several mental states that silence can reflect that are both probative of guilt and not consistent with the desire to refuse to answer the question as a matter of right.","start":3186.605,"stop":3196.294,"duration":9.69},{"text":"So, for instance, the suspect could want to answer the question but have trouble coming up with an exculpatory answer.","start":3196.294,"stop":3202.198,"duration":5.9},{"text":"He could strategically decide that he is just going to sit silent for a bit, to see what else the prosecution -- or, I'm sorry -- the police say in order to spin it out, see what they know.","start":3202.198,"stop":3211.987,"duration":9.79},{"text":"He could be dismayed or shocked momentarily because the question reveals that the police have more evidence than he thought they did.","start":3211.987,"stop":3219.041,"duration":7.05},{"text":"So I think in all of those situations, those -- those mental states are not consistent with the desire to invoke the privilege, and that's why Petitioner's rule is essentially a prophylactic rule that would protect a great deal of conduct that has nothing to do with the desire to exercise the Fifth Amendment right.","start":3219.041,"stop":3235.085,"duration":16.04},{"text":"I think this case is a good example of that, where you have a -- a suspect who speaks for, you know, several minutes, you know, half an hour, whatever, and he's answering questions in an exculpatory manner.","start":3235.085,"stop":3248.477,"duration":13.39},{"text":"He's suddenly silent in response to one question, and so I think the inference that could be drawn there is that he was surprised by the question and didn't know how to answer it in the most exculpatory manner.","start":3248.477,"stop":3259.951,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Ms. Anders, suppose, you know, he thinks that the interview is going to be one thing and then it turns out that the interview was something else.","start":3259.951,"stop":3265.771,"duration":5.82},{"text":"He realizes, it dawns on him that the police really do see him as a suspect.","start":3265.771,"stop":3271.258,"duration":5.49},{"text":"And he says to himself, I better stop answering, right?","start":3271.258,"stop":3274.294,"duration":3.04},{"text":"So he says, okay -- he's answered a bunch of questions already, but -- but now he's -- you know, I don't want to answer any more questions.","start":3274.294,"stop":3283.066,"duration":8.77},{"text":"Is that an invocation?","start":3283.066,"stop":3283.633,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that would be sufficient, yes, to say, I don't want to answer any more questions.","start":3283.633,"stop":3287.268,"duration":3.64},{"text":"And I think--","start":3287.268,"stop":3288.054,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Or if he says, I don't want to answer questions about a particular topic; is that an invocation?","start":3288.054,"stop":3292.839,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think that would be sufficient to invoke with respect to questions on that topic.","start":3292.839,"stop":3297.41,"duration":4.57},{"text":"And I think, as -- as in Thompkins, I think it's important to have a clear rule here, because invocation does affect--","start":3297.41,"stop":3303.33,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"That doesn't sound like a clear rule.","start":3303.33,"stop":3304.58,"duration":1.25},{"text":"I mean, you know, as -- as between, you know, I don't want to answer those questions on a particular topic, I don't want to answer that question, or just like could we go on to a different question or -- or I don't know.","start":3304.58,"stop":3318.156,"duration":13.58},{"text":"Why is that different?","start":3318.156,"stop":3320.023,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think it's -- it's an objective standard and it's the same formulation that the Court has already adopted in Berghuis and in Thompkins and in Davis.","start":3320.023,"stop":3327.845,"duration":7.82},{"text":"So in the Miranda context, the Court has already faced this problem: How do we know when the defendant has invoked his rights and what should the standard be?","start":3327.845,"stop":3336.368,"duration":8.52},{"text":"And it has said that it is an objective standard, it's what's reasonably perceived as an invocation, and so the lower courts are very used to applying that.","start":3336.368,"stop":3342.872,"duration":6.5},{"text":"I think it's very administrable because--","start":3342.872,"stop":3344.974,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What's not administrable about telling the police you just can't argue to a jury that merely not asking a question is guilt?","start":3344.974,"stop":3354.346,"duration":9.37},{"text":"What -- what lacks administrable?","start":3354.346,"stop":3358.816,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I -- I think there are a variety of circumstances in which, as I said before, silence is probative of guilt.","start":3358.816,"stop":3365.304,"duration":6.49},{"text":"And so the question is whether you want a broad, prophylactic rule that will protect a great deal of conduct that -- that has nothing to do with the exercise of the right.","start":3365.304,"stop":3372.641,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3372.641,"stop":3373.66,"duration":1.02},{"text":"Mr. Fisher, you have four minutes remaining.","start":3373.66,"stop":3375.826,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":3375.826,"stop":3380.064,"duration":4.24},{"text":"I'd like to make three points.","start":3380.064,"stop":3381.247,"duration":1.18},{"text":"First, Justice Breyer, your question about the state of the law with respect to question number 432.","start":3381.247,"stop":3386.967,"duration":5.72},{"text":"In our reply brief at page 4, we cite cases that are all Fifth Amendment cases, and Canterbury also, which is a Tenth Circuit case cited elsewhere in our brief, uniformly holding that the Fifth Amendment applies.","start":3386.967,"stop":3399.208,"duration":12.24},{"text":"The Solicitor General, when they speak about a circuit split with relation to Doyle, they're talking about impeachment cases.","start":3399.208,"stop":3404.095,"duration":4.89},{"text":"Remember, Doyle and Jenkins, which are the cases the State cited to you in response to your question are impeachment cases that are entirely different.","start":3404.095,"stop":3409.916,"duration":5.82},{"text":"Second, if I -- we can look at the transcript this afternoon, but I believe both the State and the Solicitor General said to you today if Mr. Salinas would have said, I don't want to answer that question, then he would win, then Griffin would apply; but because it was somehow ambiguous, that it shouldn't, that is ridiculous.","start":3409.916,"stop":3429.496,"duration":19.58},{"text":"If you look at the transcript in this case, what did the officer testify when he said -- he asked him the question, he said he did not answer.","start":3429.496,"stop":3437.583,"duration":8.09},{"text":"What did the prosecutor argue to the jury in closing?","start":3437.583,"stop":3439.685,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Verbatim of what the State is telling you today is all Mr. Salinas had to say.","start":3439.685,"stop":3444.137,"duration":4.45},{"text":"At closing the State said, the police officer testified that he wouldn't answer that question.","start":3444.137,"stop":3448.708,"duration":4.57},{"text":"He didn't want to answer that.","start":3448.708,"stop":3450.493,"duration":1.78},{"text":"So the whole principle behind express invocation jurisprudence is to put the State and the police on fair notice that somebody is exercising the right to remain silent.","start":3450.493,"stop":3460.116,"duration":9.62},{"text":"There was zero ambiguity in this case that was going on.","start":3460.116,"stop":3463.468,"duration":3.35},{"text":"So it explains why the rule that the State and the Solicitor General have fallen back on in court today is formalism of the absolute worst kind, and the only thing that this formal requirement of saying some sort of magic words -- and I agree with Justice Kagan, I don't know what they are -- but whatever they are, what -- exactly what the State argued to the jury apparently would have been enough, is just nothing more than a trap for the unwary, who is told through culture and learning that he has a right to remain silent.","start":3463.468,"stop":3493.403,"duration":29.93},{"text":"And he does the one thing that is consistent with his right, which is exercising it, and somehow the State is telling you that it can walk into court and say, because he remains silent, he's guilty of a crime.","start":3493.403,"stop":3504.895,"duration":11.49},{"text":"Jury, you should conclude he's guilty of a crime.","start":3504.895,"stop":3506.83,"duration":1.93},{"text":"And, Justice Sotomayor, when you asked the State, well, what about an officer that tells the defendant, as he will have every incentive to do, in South Carolina v. Neville in a roughly comparable situation that law enforcement actually admitted they were already doing it, but the States tell you they'll do it here, when the officer says, if you don't answer, we're going to use that against you, the State said that would be coercion.","start":3506.83,"stop":3528.093,"duration":21.26},{"text":"But the officer would be doing nothing more than stating the rule the Court is asking you to announce today.","start":3528.093,"stop":3533.647,"duration":5.55},{"text":"So wouldn't the defendant know the law?","start":3533.647,"stop":3535.766,"duration":2.12},{"text":"Don't we assume that the suspect knows the law?","start":3535.766,"stop":3538.516,"duration":2.75},{"text":"And the State's telling you, well, if the officer tells the person what the law is, it's coercion.","start":3538.516,"stop":3543.603,"duration":5.09},{"text":"So really, what we're asking today is nothing radical.","start":3543.603,"stop":3547.657,"duration":4.05},{"text":"It's nothing of a departure of our deepest traditions, which require the Government to shoulder the load itself, to prove the case itself, and not to enlist the defendant as an instrument in his own demise.","start":3547.657,"stop":3559.981,"duration":12.32},{"text":"People's silence, it is the time-honored concept of the Fifth Amendment which, remember, was created for out-of-court questioning by law enforcement authorities, that people who remain silent could not have that used against them at trial.","start":3559.981,"stop":3575.307,"duration":15.33},{"text":"And finally, I hope the -- the confusion with respect to the Berghuis as related to this case has been dispelled.","start":3575.307,"stop":3582.295,"duration":6.99},{"text":"I think Justice Kagan got it exactly right.","start":3582.295,"stop":3584.413,"duration":2.12},{"text":"But remember, another way to make it clear is that if Mr. Salinas had said in response to the question, I'd like for you to stop asking me questions, the police wouldn't have had to honor that.","start":3584.413,"stop":3595.554,"duration":11.14},{"text":"Somebody not in custody doesn't have a right to have questioning cut off, so the police could have kept asking him questions.","start":3595.554,"stop":3600.708,"duration":5.15},{"text":"That's the only right that a custodial suspect has and needs to expressly invoke.","start":3600.708,"stop":3605.243,"duration":4.53},{"text":"The right to remain silent is not something that's ever had to be expressly invoked by somebody in custody or not in custody, and there's no good reason to require it to be invoked here.","start":3605.243,"stop":3615.634,"duration":10.39},{"text":"If the Court has any further questions, I'd be happy to entertain them.","start":3615.634,"stop":3619.753,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Otherwise, I'll submit the case.","start":3619.753,"stop":3620.886,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll like to go back to what Justice Ginsburg argued, because there is an argument here that there wasn't an invocation of the right, that by physical conduct, there was a statement.","start":3620.886,"stop":3635.945,"duration":15.06},{"text":"Would you have had a problem if the prosecutor had argued at trial, you know, when he was asked about this testing, he didn't remain silent, he got nervous.","start":3635.945,"stop":3648.605,"duration":12.66}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that would be--","start":3648.605,"stop":3649.989,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"And that shows his guilt.","start":3649.989,"stop":3651.641,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Jeffrey L. Fisher","textObjs":[{"text":"--That would be an entirely different case.","start":3651.641,"stop":3652.974,"duration":1.33},{"text":"And we wouldn't have a problem with the State making legitimate arguments based on demeanor evidence that is itself communicative as opposed to what it did in this case, which is argue that his silence demonstrated his guilt.","start":3652.974,"stop":3663.799,"duration":10.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3663.799,"stop":3664.749,"duration":0.95},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3664.749,"stop":3665.817,"duration":1.07}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Apr 17, 2013","petitioner":"Genovevo Salinas","respondent":"Texas","docket":"12-246","citation":"570 US _ (2013)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/570/12-246","lowerCourt":"Texas Court of Criminal Appeals","grantedOn":"Jan 11, 2013","decidedOn":"Jun 17, 2013"}